# Nebularr Security Guardrails

- Treat security as priority #1: least privilege, minimal attack surface, defense in depth.
- Never run the FastAPI app container as root. Require non-root runtime user (prefer `1001:1001`).
- Prefer multi-stage Docker builds; keep runtime image minimal and free of build/test tooling.
- Require `.dockerignore` to exclude local envs, caches, VCS data, and frontend dev artifacts (for example `frontend/node_modules`).
- For Docker Compose changes, prefer `read_only: true`, `cap_drop: [ALL]`, `security_opt: [no-new-privileges:true]`, minimal published ports, and optional admin surfaces.
- Never hardcode credentials or secrets in source, migrations, SQL bootstrap, docs examples, or defaults presented as production-safe.
- Enforce webhook secret validation and request size limits for webhook endpoints.
- Keep PostgreSQL permissions least-privilege; avoid broad grants unless explicitly justified.
- For dependency changes (`pyproject.toml`, Python lockfiles, `frontend/package.json`, JS lockfiles), run vulnerability scans and report package deltas.
- If scanners find HIGH/CRITICAL issues, prioritize targeted fixes and re-scan before considering work complete.

## Required Verification Before Finalizing Security-Sensitive Changes

- `docker run --rm -v "$PWD:/src" aquasec/trivy:latest fs --scanners vuln,misconfig,secret --severity HIGH,CRITICAL /src`
- `docker run --rm -i hadolint/hadolint < Dockerfile`
- `docker run --rm -v "$PWD:/project" -w /project anchore/grype:latest dir:. -o table`
- `docker build -t nebularr:security-check .` then Trivy image scan (tar input acceptable)
- Backend checks: `ruff check src tests`, `mypy src`, `pytest -q`
- Frontend checks: `npm run lint`, `npm run test`, `npm audit --omit=dev --audit-level=high`

If any required command cannot run, explicitly report why, provide zero-install alternative commands, and mark residual risk.
